<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870113-0118 </DOCNO><HL>  </HL><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> FOOD andamp; BEVERAGE, HOUSEHOLD GOODS, SUPERMARKETS, TOBACCO (FAB)SUPREME COURT (SUP) </IN><TEXT>   The Supreme Court yesterday chucked one of the theories driving the tort liability explosion -- that people don't have to read warnings. The justices refused to reconsider a lower-court case saying that tobacco companies can't be sued on the ground of inadequate warning. The federal government requires that cigarette packs say the surgeon general has determined that smoking is dangerous to your health. People can smoke if they want, but their lawyers can't say they weren't warned. </TEXT></DOC>